thor></entry><entry><title type="html">What We’re Reading: What are you waiting for?</title><link href="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-what-are-you-waiting-for/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="What We’re Reading: What are you waiting for?"/><published>2023-07-14T16:42:36+00:00</published><updated>2023-07-14T16:42:36+00:00</updated><id>https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-what-are-you-waiting-for</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-what-are-you-waiting-for/"><![CDATA[]]></content><author><name></name></author></entry><entry><title type="html">a post with bibliography</title><link href="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/post-bibliography/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="a post with bibliography"/><published>2023-07-12T13:56:00+00:00</published><updated>2023-07-12T13:56:00+00:00</updated><id>https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/post-bibliography</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/post-bibliography/"><![CDATA[<p>This post shows how to add bibliography to simple blog posts. If you would like something more academic, check the <a href="/homepage/blog/2021/distill/">distill style post</a>.</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="sample-posts"/><category term="formatting"/><category term="bib"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[an example of a blog post with bibliography]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">What We’re Reading: How to get better at taking time off</title><link href="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-how-to-get-better-at-taking-time-off/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="What We’re Reading: How to get better at taking time off"/><published>2023-07-07T23:12:31+00:00</published><updated>2023-07-07T23:12:31+00:00</updated><id>https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-how-to-get-better-at-taking-time-off</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-how-to-get-better-at-taking-time-off/"><![CDATA[]]></content><author><name></name></author></entry><entry><title type="html">a post with jupyter notebook</title><link href="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/jupyter-notebook/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="a post with jupyter notebook"/><published>2023-07-04T12:57:00+00:00</published><updated>2023-07-04T12:57:00+00:00</updated><id>https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/jupyter-notebook</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/jupyter-notebook/"><![CDATA[<p>To include a jupyter notebook in a post, you can use the following code:</p> <div class="language-html highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>{::nomarkdown}
{% assign jupyter_path = "assets/jupyter/blog.ipynb" | relative_url %}
{% capture notebook_exists %}{% file_exists assets/jupyter/blog.ipynb %}{% endcapture %}
{% if notebook_exists == "true" %}
    {% jupyter_notebook jupyter_path %}
{% else %}
    <span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>Sorry, the notebook you are looking for does not exist.<span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
{% endif %}
{:/nomarkdown}
</code></pre></div></div> <p>Let’s break it down: this is possible thanks to <a href="https://github.com/red-data-tools/jekyll-jupyter-notebook">Jekyll Jupyter Notebook plugin</a> that allows you to embed jupyter notebooks in your posts. It basically calls <a href="https://nbconvert.readthedocs.io/en/latest/usage.html#convert-html"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">jupyter nbconvert --to html</code></a> to convert the notebook to an html page and then includes it in the post. Since <a href="https://jekyllrb.com/docs/configuration/markdown/">Kramdown</a> is the default Markdown renderer for Jekyll, we need to surround the call to the plugin with the <a href="https://kramdown.gettalong.org/syntax.html#extensions">::nomarkdown</a> tag so that it stops processing this part with Kramdown and outputs the content as-is.</p> <p>The plugin takes as input the path to the notebook, but it assumes the file exists. If you want to check if the file exists before calling the plugin, you can use the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">file_exists</code> filter. This avoids getting a 404 error from the plugin and ending up displaying the main page inside of it instead. If the file does not exist, you can output a message to the user. The code displayed above outputs the following:</p> <div class="jupyter-notebook" style="position: relative; width: 100%; margin: 0 auto;"> <div class="jupyter-notebook-iframe-container"> <iframe src="/homepage/assets/jupyter/blog.ipynb.html" style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border-style: none;" width="100%" height="100%" onload="this.parentElement.style.paddingBottom = (this.contentWindow.document.documentElement.scrollHeight + 10) + 'px'"></iframe> </div> </div> <p>Note that the jupyter notebook supports both light and dark themes.</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="sample-posts"/><category term="formatting"/><category term="jupyter"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[an example of a blog post with jupyter notebook]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">What We’re Reading: The Mid-Year Reset</title><link href="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-the-mid-year-reset/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="What We’re Reading: The Mid-Year Reset"/><published>2023-06-30T22:29:40+00:00</published><updated>2023-06-30T22:29:40+00:00</updated><id>https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-the-mid-year-reset</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-the-mid-year-reset/"><![CDATA[]]></content><author><name></name></author></entry><entry><title type="html">What We’re Reading: Why does the Titanic fascinate us?</title><link href="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-why-does-the-titanic-fascinate-us/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="What We’re Reading: Why does the Titanic fascinate us?"/><published>2023-06-23T23:27:16+00:00</published><updated>2023-06-23T23:27:16+00:00</updated><id>https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-why-does-the-titanic-fascinate-us</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/what-were-reading-why-does-the-titanic-fascinate-us/"><![CDATA[]]></content><author><name></name></author></entry><entry><title type="html">Register now for Medium Day</title><link href="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/register-now-for-medium-day/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Register now for Medium Day"/><published>2023-06-21T14:42:11+00:00</published><updated>2023-06-21T14:42:11+00:00</updated><id>https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/register-now-for-medium-day</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://zebiao1998.github.io/homepage/blog/2023/register-now-for-medium-day/"><![CDATA[]]></content><author><name></name></author></entry><entry><title type="html">What We’re Reading: Summer Nostalgia: Super Mario, 